This is the honest truth, brands don’t take Canadians seriously and it’s still something we’re breaking through (yes I’m Canadian for those of you who are new to my page lol). 

I’ve had multiple brands hit me up and give me a budget that was extremely low and those exact same brands will go to one of my colleagues in the states and offer them a higher budget. Now this has nothing do with my colleagues because they produce great work but it’s just interesting to see those same brands ask me to do the same amount of work or more and give me a way lower budget. 

Me being from Canada or any other country shouldn’t determine my budget or rate, the content I post and the VALUE I bring to the table should. Great content is great content and we should be paid for such. However do I feel like you need to move to the states to make more money? Not necessarily especially if brand deals are not your only source of income. This is why it’s crucial to get into digital products because brand deals could be a HIT or miss, digital products like an e-book or guide book live forever.

DISCIPLINE.

I had the pleasure of telling my story to an amazing group with @blackkingsblackqueensmovement and it was nothing but a MOMENT. 

I would’ve never imagined that my life would be like this years later after being bullied and teased for being the guy who dressed different, being the guy who looked different, being the guy who acted different. I fought for YEARS when it came to loving myself because everyone told me my personality was too “soft” or “flamboyant” when I was really just being me. 

What a lot of you don’t know, when I first started, fashion really used to be an escape for me. It was the only thing that made me feel better about who I was. Dressing nice and being different was a defence mechanism to creep over my depression. 

I was angry for YEARS because I didn’t understand how someone like myself was constantly bullied for trying new things and being creative. Not only that, I was in touch with my feelings and people didn’t like that either so instantly I was judged and it was mess. 

It wasn’t until I started opening up my Bible and praying to God and things instantly shifted. Years later it’s a full circle moment because the same thing I was bullied for, became my FULL time income. 

Being a black male influencer isn’t always the easiest, but I know my worth and I know what I’m capable of. I bring many things to the table and I’m going to continue to shift that narrative so the black influencers + content creators AFTER me have a dominate space in the community.
